[[File:Pinakothek_der_Moderne,_München_Lichtkuppel_der_Rotunde.jpg|thumb]]
[[File:Pinakothek_der_Moderne_Nord.jpg|thumb]]

'''现代艺术陈列馆'''（'''Pinakothek der Moderne'''）是德国慕尼黑的一个现代艺术博物馆，位于该市市中心，与[[老绘画陈列馆|老绘画陈列馆]]（Alte Pinakothek）、[[新绘画陈列馆|新绘画陈列馆]]（Neue Pinakothek）一起组成该市的[[艺术区|艺术区]]（Kunstareal）。

{{transH}}
== 建筑 ==
Designed by 德国建筑师[[Stephan_Braunfels|Stephan Braunfels]],现代艺术陈列馆was inaugurated in September [[2002|2002]] after 7年 of construction. The rectilinear facade, dominated by white and grey concrete, is interrupted by large windows and highrising columns, the latter supporting the extensive canopied roof. Each of the four corners of the building, connected by a 中央的圆形大厅, is dedicated to a special collection.陈列馆分为艺术、建筑、设计和 Works on Paper (Graphik). 

== 收藏 ==
现代艺术陈列馆unifies the "Sammlung Moderne Kunst" ('''National Collection of Modern and Contemporary Arts''', which  is under supervision of the Bavarian State Painting Collections),  the "Staatliche Graphische Sammlung" ('''National Collection of Works on Paper'''), the "Neue Sammlung" ('New Collection': '''National Museum for Design and Applied Arts''') with "Architekturmuseum der Technischen Universität" (Munich Technical University's 建筑博物馆), in one building and is deemed one of 最重要的欧洲现代艺术博物馆。

=== 现代艺术收藏 ===
 与其它城市相比，慕尼黑受到纳粹政权查禁现代艺术的影响较小 "[[degenerate_art|degenerate art]]," since only a few modern paintings were already collected by the "[[Hugo_von_Tschudi|Tschudi Contribution]]" in 1905/1914. Since 1945, however, the collection, previously exhibited in the [[Haus_der_Kunst|Haus der Kunst]], has grown quickly by purchase, as well as donations by individuals and several foundations. Various [[art_movement|art movement]]s of the 20th century are represented in the collection, including [[Expressionism|Expressionism]], [[Fauvism|Fauvism]], [[Cubism|Cubism]], [[New_Objectivity|New Objectivity]], [[Bauhaus|Bauhaus]], [[Surrealism|Surrealism]], [[Abstract_Expressionism|Abstract Expressionism]], [[Pop_Art|Pop Art]] and [[Minimal_Art|Minimal Art]]. 

The first floor of the west wing displays works of [[Pablo_Picasso|Pablo Picasso]], [[Henri_Matisse|Henri Matisse]], [[Georges_Braque|Georges Braque]], [[Fernand_Léger|Fernand Léger]], [[Juan_Gris|Juan Gris]], [[Umberto_Boccioni|Umberto Boccioni]], [[Robert_Delaunay|Robert Delaunay]], [[Joan_Miró|Joan Miró]] and [[René_Magritte|René Magritte]] as well as [[Max_Beckmann|Max Beckmann]], [[Lyonel_Feininger|Lyonel Feininger]], [[Oskar_Kokoschka|Oskar Kokoschka]], [[László_Moholy-Nagy|László Moholy-Nagy]], [[Otto_Dix|Otto Dix]], [[Max_Ernst|Max Ernst]], [[Giorgio_de_Chirico|Giorgio de Chirico]], [[Salvador_Dalí|Salvador Dalí]] and [[Francis_Bacon_(painter)|Francis Bacon]]. 

The museum also displays masterpieces of ''German [[Expressionism|Expressionism]]'': representing painters of two early 20th century German artist groups, [[Die_Brücke|Die Brücke]] (The bridge) and [[Der_Blaue_Reiter|Der Blaue Reiter]] (The blue rider), whose members included, among others, [[Ernst_Ludwig_Kirchner|Ernst Ludwig Kirchner]], [[Erich_Heckel|Erich Heckel]], [[Karl_Schmidt-Rottluff|Karl Schmidt-Rottluff]], [[Emil_Nolde|Emil Nolde]] and [[Franz_Marc|Franz Marc]], [[August_Macke|August Macke]], [[Paul_Klee|Paul Klee]], [[Alexej_von_Jawlensky|Alexej von Jawlensky]] and [[Wassily_Kandinsky|Wassily Kandinsky]].
*'''Contemporary Art''' since the 1960s
The museum also gives very profound insights into international contemporary art. In the first floor of the east wing the gallery displays works of [[Lucio_Fontana|Lucio Fontana]], [[Alberto_Burri|Alberto Burri]], [[Jannis_Kounellis|Jannis Kounellis]], [[Andy_Warhol|Andy Warhol]], [[Jasper_Johns|Jasper Johns]], [[Robert_Rauschenberg|Robert Rauschenberg]], [[Robert_Motherwell|Robert Motherwell]], [[Franz_Kline|Franz Kline]], [[Antoni_Tàpies|Antoni Tàpies]], [[Cy_Twombly|Cy Twombly]], [[Willem_de_Kooning|Willem de Kooning]], [[George_Segal_(artist)|George Segal]], [[Richard_Serra|Richard Serra]], [[Dan_Flavin|Dan Flavin]], [[Donald_Judd|Donald Judd]], [[Fred_Sandback|Fred Sandback]], [[Joseph_Beuys|Joseph Beuys]], [[Blinky_Palermo|Blinky Palermo]], [[Henry_Moore|Henry Moore]], [[Marino_Marini|Marino Marini]], [[Per_Kirkeby|Per Kirkeby]], [[Georg_Baselitz|Georg Baselitz]], [[Gerhard_Richter|Gerhard Richter]], [[Sigmar_Polke|Sigmar Polke]], [[Bruce_Nauman|Bruce Nauman]], [[Marlene_Dumas|Marlene Dumas]], [[Günther_Förg|Günther Förg]], [[Jörg_Immendorff|Jörg Immendorff]], [[Mike_Kelley|Mike Kelley]], [[Martin_Kippenberger|Martin Kippenberger]], [[David_Salle|David Salle]], [[Rosemarie_Trockel|Rosemarie Trockel]], [[David_Hockney|David Hockney]], [[Hermann_Nitsch|Hermann Nitsch]] and many others.
* '''Video, Photos and New Media'''
The Pinakothek houses works of artists like [[John_Baldessari|John Baldessari]] ("Man running/Men carrying box" 1988-1990), [[Bruce_Nauman|Bruce Nauman]] ("World Peace (projected)" 1996), [[Pipilotti_Rist|Pipilotti Rist]] ("Himalaya Goldsteins Stube" 1998/1999), [[Hiroshi_Sugimoto|Hiroshi Sugimoto]] ("World Trade Center, Minoru Yamazaki" 1997), [[Bill_Viola|Bill Viola]] ("Tiny Death" 1993), [[Sam_Taylor-Wood|Sam Taylor-Wood]] ("Soliloquy III" 1998) and [[Jeff_Wall|Jeff Wall]] with his back-lit boxes ("Eviction Struggle" 1988; "A villager from Aricaköyu arriving in Mahmutbey, Istanbul September 1997") 

=== Collection of works on paper ===
The Bavarian State collection of work on paper has its origin in the [[Wittelsbach|Wittelsbach]] collections, especially in the print room collection of [[Charles_Theodore,_Elector_of_Bavaria|Charles Theodore, Elector of Bavaria]].
The ground floor shows alternating exhibitions of one of the most important collection of works on paper in Germany, with old German, Dutch and Italian drawings ( including masterpieces of [[Albrecht_Dürer|Albrecht Dürer]], [[Rembrandt|Rembrandt]], [[Michelangelo|Michelangelo]] and [[Leonardo_da_Vinci|Leonardo da Vinci]] ) and German and international drawings of the 19th - 21st century, e.g. from [[Paul_Cezanne|Paul Cezanne]], [[Henri_Matisse|Henri Matisse]], [[Paul_Klee|Paul Klee]] and [[David_Hockney|David Hockney]]. 

=== 图案设计收藏 ===
[[File:Pinak_mue.jpg|thumb]]
 The Collection of applied modernist art was founded in 1925. With around 70.000 objects of [[industrial_design|industrial design]], [[graphic_design|graphic design]] and the arts and crafts the "Neue Sammlung" is today one of the world's leading museums of 20th century [[applied_art|applied art]], and indeed the largest of industrial design. Parts of the expanded collection are exhibited in the basement of the Pinakothek der Moderne. Among others objects about motor vehicle design, computer culture, design of artistic jewelry and furnitures (e.g. the collection of chairs of [[Michael_Thonet|Michael Thonet]]) are exhibited. 

=== 建筑博物馆 ===
The museum of the [[Technical_University_of_Munich|Technical University of Munich]] started with a donation of King [[Ludwig_II_of_Bavaria|Ludwig II of Bavaria]] for the newly-founded university in [[1868|1868]] and is today the largest one in Germany. The museum shows altering exhibitions in the ground floor. The collection shows especially drawings, blueprints, photographs, models and computer animations about the work of notable architects like [[François_de_Cuvilliés|François de Cuvilliés]], [[Balthasar_Neumann|Balthasar Neumann]], [[Gottfried_Semper|Gottfried Semper]], [[Le_Corbusier|Le Corbusier]] or [[Günther_Behnisch|Günther Behnisch]]. 

